 extension of possible applications for them, not only in semantics but also in syntax. At the same time questions concerning the ontological status of events have received renewed attention. This collection of articles provides new evidence for the virtually ubiquitous presence of event arguments in linguistic structure and sheds new light on their nature. The volume is organized into four sections: Events - states - causation; Event nominals; Events in composition; Measuring events.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aGrammar, Comparative and generalxVerbvCongresses. 0aSemanticsvCongresses. 4aDarstellungsart. 4aDavidson, Donald (Philosoph). 4aHandlungstheoretische Semantik. 4aMünchen ‹2004›. 4aTextlinguistik. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / General.2bisacsh1 aAbraham, Werner, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAlexiadou, Artemis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBierwisch, Manfred, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCaudal, Patrick, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEckardt, Regine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEngelberg, Stefan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGonzàlez-Vilbazo, Kay-Eduardo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHole, Daniel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKaufmann, Ingrid, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKratzer, Angelika, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLohnstein, Horst, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMaienborn, Claudia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocab